			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/other-topics/corporate-governance-other-topics/">Corporate Governance</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">In Japan, Hundreds of Shareholder Meetings on Same Day</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Hiroko Tabuchi			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-23T17:06:53+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 23, 2014 1:06 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 23, 2014 1:06 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/in-japan-hundreds-of-shareholder-meetings-on-same-day/" data-title="In Japan, Hundreds of Shareholder Meetings on Same Day" data-description="This year, more than one in three companies traded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange will hold their meetings on Friday. Experts say the practice underscores Japanese companiesâ dismissive attitude toward shareholders.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-yen2/dbpix-yen2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-yen2/dbpix-yen2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-yen2/dbpix-yen2-blog480.jpg" id="100000002958419" width="480" height="311" alt="Stock prices are displayed at a securities firm in Tokyo."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="311"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Stock prices are displayed at a securities firm in Tokyo.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Eugene Hoshiko/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investors who own shares in Japanese corporations might want to clear their calendars next Friday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At 10 a.m. on June 27, annual shareholdersâ meetings kick off at more than 900 major Japanese companies across the country. Thatâs more than one in three <a href="//www.tse.or.jp/english/listing/annual/index.html">companies traded</a> on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The herding behavior has long been practiced by Japanese corporations to make sure that as few pesky investors as possible &#8212; not to mention news reporters &#8212; turn up at their meetings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The practice was originally justified by companies as a protection against professional racketeers who sought to extort money from companies with the threat of disrupting the shareholders&#8217; meetings. But the racketeers no longer pose much of a threat, and experts say the lingering practice underscores Japanese companiesâ dismissive attitude toward shareholders. Usually poorly attended, shareholder meetings in Japan tend to be choreographed affairs, with the voting dominated by an  insidersâ club of lenders, suppliers and customers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Those tepid meetings are just one of a bevy of unfriendly arrangements investors face in Japan, including a lack of independent directors, &#8220;poison pills&#8221; that can dilute shareholders&#8217; stake and a general lack of regard for corporate governance, all of which have played in role in the chronically low returns on equity at Japanese corporations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The average return on equity measures at listed Japanese companies, excluding those in the financial sector, hovers at around 5 percent, compared with more than 15 percent at listed companies in the United States, according to the Life Insurance Association of Japan.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-olympus/dbpix-olympus-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-olympus/dbpix-olympus-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-olympus/dbpix-olympus-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002957862" width="190" height="127" alt="Michael Woodford was fired as chief executive of Olympus in 2012 after he raised questions about dubious accounting at the company."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Michael Woodford was fired as chief executive of Olympus in 2012 after he raised questions about dubious accounting at the company.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Finbarr O'Reilly/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And scandals over the years at Japanese companies &#8212; like a $1.7 billion accounting scandal at Olympus, which came to light in 2011 only after its own president blew the whistle on a scheme to hide losses for decades &#8212; have cast a harsh light on the state of corporate oversight in Japan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Prime Minister Shinzo Abe of Japan is trying to change corporate practices as part of his âAbenomicsâ agenda, with the aim of getting a long-sluggish Japanese economy to grow again.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As part of a wider reform agenda set to be approved later this month, Japan is adopting what proponents say is a world-class set of corporate governance practices, including stronger protection for whistle-blowers and new rules for directors&#8217; training and qualifications.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There may be little that Mr. Abe can do to encourage companies to stagger their shareholder meetings, but proponents say these changes amount to big steps forward for shareholder rights in Japan, home to the worldâs biggest stock market after the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Japanâs financial regulator has already published a âstewardship codeâ that requires companies to  comply or explain why they cannot follow the rules. The code encourages asset owners and managers to vote, publish their voting records, monitor firms more closely &#8212; and speak up when needed. And more companies, in response, have started adding independent directors to their boards, for example, or planning shareholder meetings on weekends so more individual investors can attend.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOne should not underestimate the potential for this virtuous circle to improve productivity and profits at Japanese firms,â Nicholas Benes, representative director at the independent Board Director Training Institute of Japan, said in an e-mail. âI really think Japan has reached a crucial turning point.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shareholders in Japan already have an easier time than in the 1990s, when more than nine out of 10 traded companies held their shareholder meetings on the same day.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the time, companies justified the timing as a measure against the professional racketeers. On the morning of June 29, 2000, for example, more than 7,000 police officers were deployed across the country to beef up security for the almost 2,200 shareholdersâ meetings held that day in Japan, according to local news reports.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the police have since cracked down on those racketeers. These days, corporate management tends to be more wary of foreign activist investors &#8212; like the foreign fund managers who sided with Olympusâs ousted president, Michael Woodford, demanding answers on the accounting fraud at the camera manufacturer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Olympus had little trouble winning shareholdersâ approval for a new, self-appointed slate of directors, in a reminder of the leeway Japanese investors continue to give, even to companies that do not perform well.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Tokyo-based Olympus has since promised to strengthen its approach to corporate governance. Skeptics remain, but Olympus is at least holding its annual shareholdersâ meeting this year on June 26 &#8212; a day before the big rush.</p>
	</div>
